facts.value:
Arrived 3 Nov. 1750 from Rotterdam on the ship "Brotherhood" at the  port of Philadelphia.  He is from the original family who started the Mennonite religion. 
The graveyard that Jacob is probably buried in is the Mennonite Cemetery on West 21'st Sreet in the Borough of Northampton, Northampton Co., PA. There are ony two grave markers in this small cemetery, that of Col. John Siegfried and that of Jocob Baer, both Revolutionary War Vetereans. There is no record of others who might be interred here, as no record was made when the cemetery was covered over with fill to match the grade of 21'st Street. (This fill covered the graveyard stones included). The reason the two mentioned markers were removed and then replaced after the fill was added was the result of the D.A.R.'s insistance that these grave markers not be covered. 

Jacob was married to Maria Saunders in 1727 in Germany. He is said to have been born in St. Gall, Canton, Switzerland. Jacob arrived in Philedelphia with wife and 11 children on 3 Nov 1750 on the ship "Brotherhood". the Ship had departed Rotterdam with the last port in Cowes, England. They settled in Whitehall Twp. Bucks Co., Pa (Now Lehigh Co.) You may note that that Northampton County was formed from part of Bucks Co. in 1752 and then Lehigh Co. was formed from part of Northampton County in 1812.

Peter Showalter purchased land between 1750 and 1752 to settle his family upon, a 67 acre tract in Whitehall Twp., Northampton Co. This was along the West side of the Lehigh river. At the same time, Jacob claimed 450 acres of land for which he had no Warrant or Patent-land which William Allen purchased 12 Dec 1759 and then on 31 Dec 1759 sold to the Showalters. (150 acres to Joseph Showalter, 100 acres, to John Showalter, 100 acres, to Jacob Showalter and to Peter Bassler a Son-in-law 100 acres.) 
Jacob's handwritten will March 7,1767 and probated 28 Apr, 1773. 
Jacob spent his last days in the home of his Son-in-law Peter Basler who had married his daughter Margaret.

https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/79702960/jacob-mathias-showalter

facts.value: Johannes or John Showalter married Anna Garver about 1753 in Whitehall Twp., Northampton, Pennsylvania. After his first wife's death he married Esther Funk about 1777. In the Mennonite records it records her as the mother of the children, but this is not the case.

facts.value: She was born in St. Gall of Caton, Switzerland ....Maria married Jacob Mathias Showalter. She, along with her husband and family emigrated to the USA on the ship Brotherhood and got here Feb 3, 1750 from Germany. The story about all that is on her husband's site. They were of the Mennonite faith and like her husband she is buried in a cemetery that was put under the 21'st highway. In their wisdom someone made a horrible decision to lay all the stones down and then just cement over all of them and the grounds. So none of the names or the stones survive. Her children were: Valentine, Peter, Jacob, Christian, Johannes, Joseph, Daniel, Ulrich, Barbara, Margaret, Martha and Ann. The last child being born IN PA eleven children having come with them. I do not know her parents as yet.

facts.value:
Ulrick Showalter was born circa 1740 and died in 1815 at Smithfield, Fayette County, Pennsylvania. His name was spelled several ways in court records, including Olerick and Woolery. Ulrick served in the Revolutionary War in Pennsylvania Line, Col. Siegfried’s Regiment. In 1790, he bought and sold 63 acres in Chester County, Pennsylvania (Note: Chester County, PA Deed Book K2, p. 171 and page 250). Ulrick had gone to Rockingham County by 1791, when he bought land from Magdalene Shaffer, widow of Nicholas Shaffer [Note: Constance A. Levinson and Louise C. Levinson, Rockingham County, Virginia Minute Book No. 2, Part I, (Harrisonburg, Virginia: Greystone Publishers), p 33]. On January 27, 1794, he was appointed by the court to appraise the estate of Henry Brunk. [Note: Constance A. Levinson and Louise C. Levinson, Rockingham County, Virginia Minute Book No. 2, Part II, (Harrisonburg, Virginia: Greystone Publishers), p.40]. Ulrick married Susannah Watterson, who was born in 1752 and died July 31, 1815. Allegedly, her parents were killed by Indians. by Wilmer L. Kerns of Arlington VA

It has been verified from the Conrad Weiser Papers in the Pennsylvania Historical Society, Vol. 2, page 115, that Susannah Watterson's parents, John and Katharine Watterson, and their infant son, were all killed by Indians on 4/4/1756 in Northampton County, PA, Only Susannah and her brother James escaped this Indian raid.


Revolutionary War Service: “List of Soldiers Who Served as Rangers on the Frontier 1778-1783” in Pennsylvania Archives, Third Series, Volume 23, page 305.  His name is in the right side column on the page. This reference by CK.


This is an excerpt from a letter written by Jake Showalter to Clyde Showalter in Sept 1893.  

"In 1729 Ulerick Showalter, at the age of 7 years, came to America from Germany with his family and settled in Virginia.  He had three brothers who came at the same time.  Ulerick had a son, John, who settled in Penn. on the farm still owned by the family."

Person #7 in The "Pennsylvania Deitsch" Family of Showalter (Floyd Howes, 1971)

From that entry:
Valentine "Felty" Showalter, son of Jacob #1, came to Chester County, Penns. about 1769 and about 1789-90 went with some of his children to Rockingham County, Virginia in the valley of the Shenandoah River, where he died in 1803. His wifes name was Anna. He lived in Tredyffine Township while living in Chester county near his brothers Daniel and John. In 1779 he was taxed in this township on 100 acres of land, 3 horses and 4 cows, and the tax list gives his occupation as a weaver. IN 1780 and 81 he was taxed on 106 acres of land. In 1771 he paid taxes on 106 acres of land, 4 horses, 4 cows, and 4 sheep.
